So what happened is, as people
get these credits in their

00:49:04.090 --> 00:49:07.300
account, they start behaving as
though that's real money.

00:49:07.300 --> 00:49:09.000
So suddenly you have all
this money stacking up.

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:11.180
And if you've taken
all sorts of--

00:49:11.180 --> 00:49:12.410
if you've made bets
with people.

00:49:12.410 --> 00:49:13.380
And you've, say--

00:49:13.380 --> 00:49:15.000
this is what happened with these
credit default swaps.

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:20.190
They'd made bets on peoples'
ability to pay a

00:49:20.190 --> 00:49:21.090
loan down the road.

00:49:21.090 --> 00:49:27.780
So say, for example, John has
bought a car, for example, and

00:49:27.780 --> 00:49:31.160
I want to bet that John's going
to crash his car within

00:49:31.160 --> 00:49:32.360
the next five years.

00:49:32.360 --> 00:49:33.310
I can take a bet with you.

00:49:33.310 --> 00:49:37.690
And I can pay you $5 a week
to take that action.

00:49:37.690 --> 00:49:40.760
So every week I'll pay you $5.

00:49:40.760 --> 00:49:44.270
And if John does crash his car,
then indeed, you pay me

00:49:44.270 --> 00:49:46.200
the entire worth
of John's car.

00:49:46.200 --> 00:49:46.660
So this is great.

00:49:46.660 --> 00:49:49.780
But what I can do is I can
register that as an asset.

00:49:49.780 --> 00:49:55.030
I can say I essentially
own the money that--

00:49:55.030 --> 00:49:56.270
so you can register
this as an asset.

00:49:56.270 --> 00:49:58.980
So what you had is all of this
financial shenanigans that

00:49:58.980 --> 00:50:05.110
allowed people to show all of
this income and this huge

00:50:05.110 --> 00:50:07.120
bottom line in their
bank accounts, and

00:50:07.120 --> 00:50:08.710
much of it was notional.

00:50:08.710 --> 00:50:11.100
It's kind of like when
you own a house and

00:50:11.100 --> 00:50:12.370
you value your house.

00:50:12.370 --> 00:50:13.310
And you say--

00:50:13.310 --> 00:50:15.640
you bought the house
for $300,000.

00:50:15.640 --> 00:50:17.160
Then the market jacks
up and now the

00:50:17.160 --> 00:50:19.090
house is worth $600,000.

00:50:19.090 --> 00:50:21.660
So you take the equity out
and then the house

00:50:21.660 --> 00:50:23.270
drops back down again.

00:50:23.270 --> 00:50:27.040
Well, that house was never
really worth $600,000.

00:50:27.040 --> 00:50:28.250
But yet, you've taken
the money out of it.

00:50:28.250 --> 00:50:29.990
And now your houses is under
water and you owe that money

00:50:29.990 --> 00:50:30.810
back in again.

00:50:30.810 --> 00:50:33.130
That's the kind of place where
all the money disappeared.

00:50:33.130 --> 00:50:37.360
It was this notional concept of
the value of certain assets

00:50:37.360 --> 00:50:39.740
that just disappeared whenever
the market dropped away.

00:50:39.740 --> 00:50:41.200
And that didn't just
happen in housing.

00:50:41.200 --> 00:50:44.370
That happened for cars
in many cases.

00:50:44.370 --> 00:50:46.340
It certainly happened for
credit default swaps.

00:50:46.340 --> 00:50:48.810
It happened for stocks
and shares and bonds.

00:50:48.810 --> 00:50:50.150
All sorts of assets.

00:50:50.150 --> 00:50:52.080
So this is what they call--

00:50:52.080 --> 00:50:54.145
this is where you hear the term
"frothy" in the market.

00:50:54.145 --> 00:50:57.500
It was just like froth
on the top of a beer.

00:50:57.500 --> 00:50:58.890
That froth looks great.

00:50:58.890 --> 00:50:59.970
The beer's this big.

00:50:59.970 --> 00:51:01.610
The froth just sort of
slowly goes down.

00:51:01.610 --> 00:51:03.430
And that's it.

00:51:03.430 --> 00:51:04.630
That's what happens.

00:51:04.630 --> 00:51:07.110
So it's all that froth that
we're talking about.

00:51:07.110 --> 00:51:08.810
So when people say, where
did all the money go?

00:51:08.810 --> 00:51:11.320
Well, the money didn't really
exist in the first place.

00:51:11.320 --> 00:51:12.791
It just looked like it did.

00:51:16.400 --> 00:51:17.710
Wow.

00:51:17.710 --> 00:51:18.960
Thanks for that.

