Definitely.

00:51:28.740 --> 00:51:30.470
We're looking for a
happy medium, yes.

00:51:30.470 --> 00:51:32.280
I think everybody's looking
for a happy medium.

00:51:32.280 --> 00:51:35.960
But I think that really, with
the way the bubbles worked--

00:51:35.960 --> 00:51:37.260
and that's one of the things
about gold standard.

00:51:37.260 --> 00:51:39.195
They said, well, there were
never any bubbles when we had

00:51:39.195 --> 00:51:40.245
a gold standard.

00:51:40.245 --> 00:51:42.610
But that's not entirely true,
because you think of the--

00:51:42.610 --> 00:51:45.750
you may have heard of the tulip
bubble in the 1500s.

00:51:45.750 --> 00:51:47.500
And they have the gold
standard then.

00:51:47.500 --> 00:51:48.670
They had a bubble then.

00:51:48.670 --> 00:51:52.700
But it was a particular
asset, the value

00:51:52.700 --> 00:51:54.710
of these tulip bulbs.

00:51:54.710 --> 00:51:57.640
So it's not entirely true that
you don't have bubbles, but

00:51:57.640 --> 00:51:59.420
you probably get less of them
with the gold standard because

00:51:59.420 --> 00:52:01.010
you don't have the ability
to print money.

00:52:06.530 --> 00:52:08.220
Well, let's deal with
the 47% first.

00:52:08.220 --> 00:52:09.020
So yes.

00:52:09.020 --> 00:52:12.860
What's really interesting about
that statement is that a

00:52:12.860 --> 00:52:14.650
significant proportion
of the 47% are

00:52:14.650 --> 00:52:15.730
probably Republican voters.

00:52:15.730 --> 00:52:19.150
It just drives-- it amazes me.

00:52:19.150 --> 00:52:21.460
This falls into the same
rubric as the, get your

00:52:21.460 --> 00:52:24.070
government hands off my
Medicare comment.

00:52:24.070 --> 00:52:27.390
It's really interesting to hear
him say that, because a

00:52:27.390 --> 00:52:29.810
lot of those people
are retired.

00:52:29.810 --> 00:52:31.730
They're not paying
any income tax.

00:52:31.730 --> 00:52:34.310
And a lot of retired voters
vote Republican.

00:52:34.310 --> 00:52:38.740
So it's crazy that he would
make that statement.

00:52:38.740 --> 00:52:41.460
I watched the entire
video, or certainly

00:52:41.460 --> 00:52:42.250
right up to that point.

00:52:42.250 --> 00:52:45.310
So I know that he wasn't quoted
out of context there.

00:52:45.310 --> 00:52:48.310
That said, it's true.

00:52:48.310 --> 00:52:51.330
We have a system that
is open to abuse.

00:52:51.330 --> 00:52:53.500
And some people do abuse it.

00:52:53.500 --> 00:52:56.480
But I don't think 47% of the
population abuses it.

00:52:56.480 --> 00:52:59.110
Now, the question about the
amount of tax that--

00:52:59.110 --> 00:53:00.780
or how you can avoid the AMT.

00:53:00.780 --> 00:53:02.590
I mean, you'd have to speak to
a tax advisor about avoiding

00:53:02.590 --> 00:53:04.440
the AMT, which I'm sure you
could do if you're--

00:53:04.440 --> 00:53:05.790
AUDIENCE: But he's done it.

00:53:05.790 --> 00:53:08.690
PADDY HIRSCH: Well, he's done
it because he doesn't get

00:53:08.690 --> 00:53:09.743
income, you see.

00:53:09.743 --> 00:53:11.370
Not in the way that
we understand it.

00:53:11.370 --> 00:53:14.670
He has this thing called
carried interest.

00:53:14.670 --> 00:53:18.170
And what this is is if you are
a private equity fund--

00:53:18.170 --> 00:53:20.870
usually, we get paid a
paycheck every month.

00:53:20.870 --> 00:53:22.730
That's how it works for us.

00:53:22.730 --> 00:53:26.550
When you're in charge of a hedge
fund, what happens is

00:53:26.550 --> 00:53:27.540
you're making investments.

00:53:27.540 --> 00:53:30.840
So as the partner in a hedge
fund, it's almost as though

00:53:30.840 --> 00:53:32.500
you're just buying stocks
and shares.

00:53:32.500 --> 00:53:33.360
You're obviously buying
more than that.

00:53:33.360 --> 00:53:35.300
But it's like you're buying
stocks and shares.

00:53:35.300 --> 00:53:38.930
And then every month, you
get paid interest.

00:53:38.930 --> 00:53:41.150
So you get paid through
interest.

00:53:41.150 --> 00:53:46.190
But interest only gets
taxed at 15%.

00:53:46.190 --> 00:53:49.190
And carried interest only occurs
once every couple of

00:53:49.190 --> 00:53:50.680
years, because the way that--

00:53:50.680 --> 00:53:53.390
I mean, I'm sure most people
know about the venture capital

00:53:53.390 --> 00:53:54.450
market more than I do now.

00:53:54.450 --> 00:53:57.410
But the way a venture capital
works is that you only get

00:53:57.410 --> 00:54:02.320
paid out as an investor whenever
the exit from the

00:54:02.320 --> 00:54:03.680
investment occurs.

00:54:03.680 --> 00:54:05.880
So that could be like two,
three, five, seven

00:54:05.880 --> 00:54:07.070
years down the line.

00:54:07.070 --> 00:54:08.880
So a lot of the time this money
is coming in a lump sum,

00:54:08.880 --> 00:54:11.810
but it's still only
investment income.

00:54:11.810 --> 00:54:15.545
He's not being paid a check
monthly by his employer, by

00:54:15.545 --> 00:54:16.850
Bain Capital.

00:54:16.850 --> 00:54:19.180
So everything for him, all of
his money, comes in through

00:54:19.180 --> 00:54:19.610
investments.

00:54:19.610 --> 00:54:22.002
And the reason I think that--

00:54:22.002 --> 00:54:24.280
this is entirely subjective
on my part, but one of the

00:54:24.280 --> 00:54:26.690
reasons I think that the
Romney campaign was so

00:54:26.690 --> 00:54:29.160
reluctant to release this
information is not because

00:54:29.160 --> 00:54:29.960
there's anything
illegal in it--

00:54:29.960 --> 00:54:31.220
I think it's completely legal.

00:54:31.220 --> 00:54:34.060
I think the scary thing is what
you can get away with

00:54:34.060 --> 00:54:35.060
that's legal.

00:54:35.060 --> 00:54:36.230
I mean, it's, really?

00:54:36.230 --> 00:54:38.790
It's like, this is legal?

00:54:38.790 --> 00:54:39.550
It's totally legal.

00:54:39.550 --> 00:54:40.520
So he didn't do anything
illegal.

00:54:40.520 --> 00:54:45.610
But I think it's really kind of
a poke in the eye for the

00:54:45.610 --> 00:54:48.090
tax regime that you can get away
with this kind of thing.

00:54:48.090 --> 00:54:50.220
And I think a lot of
people think that

00:54:50.220 --> 00:54:51.360
it's extremely unfair.

00:54:51.360 --> 00:54:52.590
But that's really where
it comes into.

00:54:52.590 --> 00:54:56.590
It is investment income,
and not earned income,

00:54:56.590 --> 00:54:57.910
as you and I have.

00:54:57.910 --> 00:54:58.920
Can we afford Obamacare?

00:54:58.920 --> 00:55:00.990
Well, we're paying
for it right now.

00:55:00.990 --> 00:55:03.230
So we've got it right now.

00:55:03.230 --> 00:55:06.710
Actually, I think that what's
really interesting about the

00:55:06.710 --> 00:55:09.620
Romney plan and Obamacare as it
exists today, there's very

00:55:09.620 --> 00:55:11.330
little to choose between
them, frankly.

00:55:11.330 --> 00:55:16.970
I mean, everybody talks about
the great saving that the Ryan

00:55:16.970 --> 00:55:18.740
plan is going to make five years
down the road, which is

00:55:18.740 --> 00:55:20.820
exactly the great saving that
Obamacare is already

00:55:20.820 --> 00:55:21.460
making right now.

00:55:21.460 --> 00:55:24.930
So I think there's not much to
choose between the two plans.

00:55:24.930 --> 00:55:27.440
Whether or not we can
afford Obamacare--

00:55:27.440 --> 00:55:28.240
I actually don't think so.

00:55:28.240 --> 00:55:30.070
I think cuts are going to have
to be a lot deeper than they

00:55:30.070 --> 00:55:31.860
are right now.

00:55:31.860 --> 00:55:37.650
Just to keep the system funded
is going to be a problem.

00:55:37.650 --> 00:55:40.330
But to keep the system funded
and to pay down the deficit to

00:55:40.330 --> 00:55:42.510
some extent is going to be
really, really hard to do.

00:55:42.510 --> 00:55:44.540
And it's clear that they're
going to have to make deeper

00:55:44.540 --> 00:55:45.390
cuts than they've
made right now.

00:55:45.390 --> 00:55:47.370
They're going to be extremely
difficult to do politically.

00:55:47.370 --> 00:55:48.410
But they've got to be done.

00:55:48.410 --> 00:55:49.320
Otherwise, the system,
I think, is

00:55:49.320 --> 00:55:50.310
going to bust itself.

00:55:50.310 --> 00:55:52.770
So I think as it stands right
now, in the situation we're in

00:55:52.770 --> 00:55:53.880
right now, probably not.

00:55:53.880 --> 00:55:54.890
No, I don't think we could.

00:55:54.890 --> 00:55:58.820
So we're going to have to make
some cuts elsewhere.

00:55:58.820 --> 00:55:59.420
All right.

00:55:59.420 --> 00:56:00.280
Thank you all very
much indeed.

00:56:00.280 --> 00:56:01.370
I really appreciate it.

00:56:01.370 --> 00:56:02.620
Thank you.

